<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="prep-10-21">
  <title>Resources for 10/21</title>

  <objectives>
    <introduction>
      <p>For the content of this class, you will be expected to be able to do the following:</p>
    </introduction>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <p>
          Solve problems involving compound interest.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Know that the function <m>f(x) = e^x</m> is the <em>natural exponential function</em>.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Explain why the function <m>f(x) = b^x</m> has an inverse when <m>b &gt; 0</m> and <m>b \ne 1</m>.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Know that the inverse of <m>f(x)</m> in this case is <m>f^{-1}(x) = \log_b(x)</m>.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Use the definition of the <em>logarithm functions</em> to compute <m>\log_b(x)</m> for certain values of <m>x</m> and <m>b</m>.
        </p>
      </li>
    </ul>
  </objectives>

  <subsection xml:id="video-activity-compound-interest-2">
    <title>Video &amp; Activities for Compound Interest (Continued from Last Class)</title>
    <p>
      Below is a YouTube video on <em>compound interest</em>. It is followed by links to two sets of activities that we will be working on in class. Please watch the video and do as many of the activities as you can before class.
    </p>

    <video youtube="IZzOgiYB4o4" />

    <example>
      <title>More Compound Interest</title>
      <p>
        Solve the following compound interest problems.
      </p>
      <p>
        <ol>
          <li>
            <p>
              Suppose that you put $150 into an account with a 10% annual interest rate that is compounded 8 times per year.
              <ol>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    After 5 years, how many times has the interest been computed and added to your total?
                  </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    What interest rate is used for each interest computation?
                  </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    What is the total in your account after 5 years?
                  </p>
                </li>
              </ol>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Suppose you put money into an account with an annual interest rate of 9% and that is compounded every two months.  After 20 months, you have $800 in your account.  How much was your initial deposit?
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Suppose you invest $1 in an interest-bearing account.
              <ol>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    If your money earns a 100% annual interest rate, how much money do you have at the end of the year when you compound it a huge number of times (try a few really big values of <m>n</m>)?  Call this number <m>e</m>.
                  </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    Do the same as in (a) except with a 50% annual interest rate.  Compare this number with <m>e^{0.5} = \sqrt{e}</m>.
                  </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    Do the same as in (a) except with a 25% annual interest rate.  Compare this number with <m>e^{0.25} = \sqrt[4]{e}</m>.
                  </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    Do the same as in (a) except with a 20% annual interest rate.  Compare this number with <m>e^{0.2} = \sqrt[5]{e}</m>.
                  </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    If you do the same as above with an annual interest rate of <m>r</m>, what do you expect the result to be?
                  </p>
                </li>
              </ol>
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </example>
    <p>
      Feel free to post any questions you have on the <url href="">FigJam board</url> for the next class.
    </p>
  </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="video-activity-intro-logarithms">
    <title>Video &amp; Introduction to Logarithms</title>
    <p>
      Below is a YouTube video introducing <em>logarithms</em>. It is followed by a link to a set of activities that we will be working on in class. Please watch the video and do as many of the activities as you can before class.
    </p>

    <video youtube="IZzOgiYB4o4" />

    <example>
      <title>Introduction to Logarithms</title>
      <p>
        In the first three problems, compute the given quantity.
      </p>
      <p>
        <ol>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>\log_3(27)</m>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>\log_2(64)</m>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>\log_{11}(121)</m>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Suppose <m>\log_a(x)=3</m> and <m>\log_a(y)=5</m>.
             <ol>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    Find an expression for <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> in terms of <m>a</m>.
                  </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    Use what you found in (a) to compute both <m>\log_a(xy)</m> and <m>\log_a \left( \frac{x}{y} \right)</m>
                  </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    Compute <m>\log_a \left( x^6 \right)</m> and <m>\log_a(y^4)</m>.
                  </p>
                </li>
              </ol>
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </example>
    <p>
      Feel free to post any questions you have on the <url href="">FigJam board</url> for the next class.
    </p>
  </subsection>

